### 🔴 346. Ship Breaking & Recycling

**What it is:** Dismantling end-of-life ships and recovering steel, copper, brass, machinery, and other materials. Alang (Gujarat) is the world's largest ship-breaking yard.

**Players:** Alang ship-breakers (many), Leela Ship Recycling (Indian), R L Kalthia (Indian).

**Model:** Arbitrage 📈 (buy ship, sell recovered materials) | **Revenue:** 🔄 Medium.

**Challenges:** 💰 Buying a ship costs ₹5Cr-100Cr+ · 📜 Ship Recycling Act + Hong Kong Convention compliance · ⚙ Extremely hazardous work (asbestos, lead, oil, falling steel) · 🧠 Estimating recoverable material value · 👥 International scrutiny on worker safety.

**Mistake:** Underestimating hazardous materials inside ships. Asbestos, lead paint, PCBs, fuel oil — all must be safely managed. Worker safety failures bring international condemnation and regulatory action.

**One-liner:** Break ships for scrap — profitable but among the most dangerous industrial activities; worker safety is paramount.

